00:03:59,055 --> 00:04:02,577
in these slides. These are not rules that are written in stone.

69
00:04:02,857 --> 00:04:06,599
They're just guiding principles. They're my undereducated opinion.

70
00:04:07,020 --> 00:04:11,382
They've been created to prompt discussion, to shed a little bit of light

71
00:04:11,422 --> 00:04:14,884
on the black art of level design, and hopefully help some people create

72
00:04:14,904 --> 00:04:18,946
some kick-ass levels along the way. So now we've got that out of the way,

73
00:04:18,966 --> 00:04:22,128
let's start with the first principle, which is

74
00:04:22,948 --> 00:04:26,170
that good level design is fun to navigate.

75
00:04:27,287 --> 00:04:31,092
Now just traversing a level presents the player with many different gameplay vectors.

76
00:04:32,053 --> 00:04:36,078
There's observational, which is the act of surveying one's surroundings.

77
00:04:37,300 --> 00:04:41,145
Strategic, the act of processing your observations into a plan.

78
00:04:41,806 --> 00:04:45,390
And then there's navigational, the act of actually traversing the level itself.

79
00:04:48,935 --> 00:04:50,816
And for a smooth and enjoyable experience,

80
00:04:51,637 --> 00:04:54,159
the player should always know exactly where to go,

81
00:04:54,680 --> 00:04:56,121
which is why it's important to develop

82
00:04:56,581 --> 00:05:00,084
a consistent visual language that clearly guides the player

83
00:05:00,445 --> 00:05:01,506
through the critical path.

84
00:05:02,486 --> 00:05:04,288
Now, different games use different methods to do this.

85
00:05:04,949 --> 00:05:08,612
But it usually comes down to the use of light, geometry, color,

86
00:05:08,952 --> 00:05:13,696
and animation, a good example of which is Mirror's Edge.

87
00:05:14,726 --> 00:05:18,149
So Mirror's Edge uses all of these things to create fantastic clarity and flow.

88
00:05:19,331 --> 00:05:22,053
If you look at this slide, it's pretty easy to work out.

89
00:05:22,113 --> 00:05:27,539
You have to climb up the red crane, run along the red crane, jump onto the red pipes, run

90
00:05:27,579 --> 00:05:31,222
along the red pipes, and then jump onto the conveniently placed soft squishy object just

91
00:05:31,282 --> 00:05:31,683
on the right.

92
00:05:33,883 --> 00:05:35,184
But the important thing to note here

93
00:05:35,904 --> 00:05:38,065
is the difference between intuitive to navigate

94
00:05:38,745 --> 00:05:39,745
and fun to navigate.

95
00:05:40,405 --> 00:05:42,066
What the player doesn't notice in the screenshot

96
00:05:42,106 --> 00:05:42,966
is equally important.

97
00:05:43,466 --> 00:05:47,547
So the hidden messenger bags, the speed paths

98
00:05:47,567 --> 00:05:49,948
that will give you achievements, and all of these

99
00:05:49,988 --> 00:05:52,309
are put in there to encourage exploration, which is

100
00:05:52,369 --> 00:05:54,489
essentially freestyle navigation.

101
00:05:55,069 --> 00:05:57,790
And this helps create depth and replayability in your levels.

102
00:05:59,411 --> 00:06:00,711
Also in contrast to this point.

103
00:06:02,249 --> 00:06:04,370
sometimes it's good to throw in a little confusion.

104
00:06:05,751 --> 00:06:05,951
Now,

105
00:06:07,112 --> 00:06:10,434
Modern Warfare 2 does this particularly well in its favela level.

106
00:06:11,374 --> 00:06:13,715
It's highly memorable for its hectic and intense gameplay.

107
00:06:14,496 --> 00:06:16,077
You're set

108
00:06:16,317 --> 00:06:19,779
in a Brazilian favela. It's a tight, twisty maze. There's no clearly

109
00:06:19,859 --> 00:06:20,759
obvious path through it.

110
00:06:21,139 --> 00:06:23,401
Enemies are coming from all sides. They're coming from behind.

111
00:06:24,061 --> 00:06:27,163
They bring versatility into the level design with enemies attacking you from above.

112
00:06:28,083 --> 00:06:30,264
Is it easy to navigate through this level? Absolutely not.

113
00:06:31,352 --> 00:06:33,153
Is it fun? Yes it is.

114
00:06:34,593 --> 00:06:37,934
And by carefully throwing in some well-considered confusion to the mix,

115
00:06:38,394 --> 00:06:41,555
Treyarch have created a really good sense of dramatic tension in this level.

116
00:06:42,996 --> 00:06:43,796
And speaking of drama,

117
00:06:45,197 --> 00:06:50,538
the second principle is that good level design does not rely on words to tell the story.

118
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:59,921
One of my mentors once told me that a good story or a good piece of communication

119
00:07:00,822 --> 00:07:02,023
is like a broken circle.

120
00:07:03,004 --> 00:07:04,285
And you give the player this circle

121
00:07:04,765 --> 00:07:07,267
and it's down to them to fill in the gap.

122
00:07:08,528 --> 00:07:09,249
Now the trick here

123
00:07:09,969 --> 00:07:11,810
is if you make the gap too big

124
00:07:12,671 --> 00:07:13,892
the player won't be able to fill it in

125
00:07:14,452 --> 00:07:16,514
and he'll feel confused and patronized.

126
00:07:17,274 --> 00:07:19,016
But if you make the gap too small

127
00:07:19,856 --> 00:07:22,558
he'll fill it in too easily and he'll be bored and he won't feel challenged.

128
00:07:23,279 --> 00:07:25,721
So, how do we do this in terms of level design?

129
00:07:26,915 --> 00:07:30,857
Well, there are three types of narrative at work in a game's level.

130
00:07:31,558 --> 00:07:34,819
There's explicit, implicit, and emergent.

131
00:07:36,520 --> 00:07:40,862
Explicit narrative is anything that's explicitly called out to the player

132
00:07:41,282 --> 00:07:45,184
through cutscenes or text or spoken dialogue

133
00:07:45,284 --> 00:07:49,966
or any written content that he or she finds.

134
00:07:51,187 --> 00:07:53,068
And it's this that creates your circle.

135
00:07:54,687 --> 00:07:58,949
Implicit is anything that the player figures out for themselves by looking at the environment.

136
00:07:59,129 --> 00:08:00,810
I'll go into this in a bit more detail in a second.

137
00:08:02,031 --> 00:08:06,433
And emergent is the story that the player makes up in his or her own head.

138
00:08:07,414 --> 00:08:11,256
Now creating the first type of narrative is pretty straightforward, but it's the other

139
00:08:11,296 --> 00:08:17,239
two types, implicit and emergent, that create that crucial gap in the circle.

140
00:08:17,259 --> 00:08:18,520
So how do we do this in a level?

141
00:08:18,540 --> 00:08:19,460
So how do we do this in a level?

142
00:08:20,865 --> 00:08:25,907
Well, the best way of creating implicit narrative is a technique called mise-en-scene,

143
00:08:26,987 --> 00:08:31,629
which has been used by stage and cinema for many, many years.

144
00:08:31,849 --> 00:08:33,990
And it's the art of telling the story through the environment.

145
00:08:34,471 --> 00:08:37,732
And I believe that some studios call this environmental narrative.

146
00:08:38,919 --> 00:08:42,602
So, for me, the master of implicit narrative is Bioshock.

147
00:08:43,283 --> 00:08:48,047
So if you look at these pictures here, you'll see there's water on the floor, which is kind of bad if you're in an underwater city.

148
00:08:48,748 --> 00:08:51,911
There are balloons on the ceiling, which means there was a party recently.

149
00:08:53,652 --> 00:08:57,296
There are creepy masks, which make you think, what kind of party was this?

150
00:08:58,236 --> 00:08:59,898
And there are drinks that have been left abandoned.

151
00:08:59,918 --> 00:09:03,041
So, clearly something went wrong, and people left in a hurry.

152
00:09:03,832 --> 00:09:07,872
What I find particularly interesting about this picture is the massive big sign on the side,

153
00:09:07,933 --> 00:09:10,153
which clearly says that it's New Year 1959,

154
00:09:10,193 --> 00:09:14,954
which tells you the exact date that everything went wrong.

155
00:09:15,294 --> 00:09:20,535
But also, even though it's almost the 60s, the decor of this environment is very much in the 40s,

156
00:09:20,575 --> 00:09:25,617
which creates an odd visual disparity and makes the player feel uneasy.

157
00:09:27,507 --> 00:09:29,629
Now it's very important that you should design your levels

158
00:09:30,169 --> 00:09:32,271
to give your world artists the opportunity

159
00:09:32,291 --> 00:09:33,532
to tell this visual story.

160
00:09:34,432 --> 00:09:38,215
But creating emergent narrative is not such an obvious task,

161
00:09:38,275 --> 00:09:40,157
because the level designer doesn't actually create it.

162
00:09:40,657 --> 00:09:44,340
He merely enables it by providing

163
00:09:44,360 --> 00:09:45,661
the player with choice.

164
00:09:46,361 --> 00:09:49,424
So Hitman is actually a great example of emergent narrative,

165
00:09:50,124 --> 00:09:51,145
as there's plenty of choice.

166
00:09:51,285 --> 00:09:54,187
So you can use any kind of game mechanic

167
00:09:54,207 --> 00:09:56,429
you like to kill your mark.

168
00:09:56,839 --> 00:09:59,522
You can poison him with a syringe, or you can poison their food.

169
00:10:00,022 --> 00:10:01,484
You can use combat mechanics, either

170
00:10:02,024 --> 00:10:03,886
uh, garrotting him with a fiber wire,

171
00:10:03,906 --> 00:10:06,589
uh, or filling him full of bullets.

172
00:10:07,069 --> 00:10:08,531
You can even use the physics to kill him,

173
00:10:09,191 --> 00:10:10,673
uh, by pushing him off a ledge,

174
00:10:11,213 --> 00:10:12,615
or by pushing something heavy onto him.

175
00:10:13,562 --> 00:10:16,743
And this is freedom of choice, an emergent style

176
00:10:17,303 --> 00:10:20,184
that's great for allowing the player to fill in the gap in your circle.

177
00:10:20,204 --> 00:10:24,005
In fact, in Hitman, you can even go in dressed as a chicken, guns blazing,

178
00:10:24,965 --> 00:10:26,605
and kill absolutely everyone in the entire level.

179
00:10:27,246 --> 00:10:29,606
Or you can sneak through the level undetected,

180
00:10:29,706 --> 00:10:31,006
dress in your immaculate black suit,

181
00:10:31,747 --> 00:10:33,727
kill only the mark, and leave through the front door

182
00:10:33,747 --> 00:10:34,827
before anyone knows you're there,

183
00:10:34,867 --> 00:10:37,048
getting that perfect silent assassin rating,

184
00:10:37,988 --> 00:10:38,508
which is great.

185
00:10:39,408 --> 00:10:41,129
But too much choice.

186
00:10:41,966 --> 00:10:44,927
can leave the player confused and in need of guidance.

187
00:10:45,847 --> 00:10:50,329
Which is why the third principle is that good level design

188
00:10:51,229 --> 00:10:55,470
always tells the player what to do, but never how to do it.

189
00:10:58,591 --> 00:11:01,292
The player needs to be in no doubt as to what he or she has to do

190
00:11:01,332 --> 00:11:02,192
when they go through your level.

191
00:11:03,353 --> 00:11:05,574
And you should provide them with clear objectives,

192
00:11:05,594 --> 00:11:08,214
so waypoints, other navigational aids, etc.

193
00:11:09,512 --> 00:11:14,935
But it is possible to create compelling challenge through obfuscation of the details.

194
00:11:15,575 --> 00:11:19,057
That is to say by providing nebulous objectives.

195
00:11:20,118 --> 00:11:22,219
So keep your guidance concise and clear.

196
00:11:22,739 --> 00:11:27,521
Only give as much information to the players as is absolutely necessary.

197
00:11:28,142 --> 00:11:31,343
But make sure you provide multiple paths and styles of approach.

198
00:11:32,537 --> 00:11:35,741
So Skyrim does this very well because of its open world nature,

199
00:11:35,801 --> 00:11:37,143
particularly the Dark Brotherhood missions,

200
00:11:37,183 --> 00:11:39,686
which are kind of like a Tolkien-esque hitman.

201
00:11:42,049 --> 00:11:44,292
They tell you exactly where you can find your mark

202
00:11:44,332 --> 00:11:45,193
and exactly who they are.

203
00:11:45,534 --> 00:11:47,576
They even appear as a mark on your compass.

204
00:11:48,535 --> 00:11:52,358
but it never forces a player to use a singular technique to carry out the execution.

205
00:11:52,778 --> 00:11:55,120
In fact, if you look at the level design for the Dark Brotherhood missions,

206
00:11:56,061 --> 00:12:00,304
very often specific alternate methods of execution have been set up.

207
00:12:00,644 --> 00:12:06,389
So there'll be an arrow, a bow rather, and a sheath of arrows on top of a ledge

208
00:12:06,429 --> 00:12:07,570
so you can strike from a distance.

209
00:12:07,950 --> 00:12:11,913
Or there'll be an opportunity to kill the target silently

210
00:12:12,253 --> 00:12:15,156
when they leave the crowd and go to a secluded spot.

211
00:12:16,411 --> 00:12:21,173
So as well as not forcing the player what to do, it's important not to punish the player for improvisation.

212
00:12:21,814 --> 00:12:27,637
If the player does something that you don't expect, you shouldn't chastise them.

213
00:12:27,797 --> 00:12:32,679
You should design it into your game and encourage player improvisation.

214
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:36,742
And all this ties in with the emergent narrative that I was talking about earlier.

215
00:12:40,614 --> 00:12:42,896
So veteran game designer, Mark Cerny,

216
00:12:43,076 --> 00:12:45,258
tells us that the player should be presented

217
00:12:45,298 --> 00:12:47,820
with concurrent objectives that can be completed

218
00:12:48,221 --> 00:12:49,842
in any order he or she wishes.

219
00:12:51,163 --> 00:12:53,925
Furthermore, on completion of one of those objectives,

220
00:12:53,945 --> 00:12:55,206
the player should receive a reward,

221
00:12:56,087 --> 00:12:58,209
which either makes the other objectives easier

222
00:12:58,349 --> 00:13:01,532
or modifies them in some way.

223
00:13:01,592 --> 00:13:04,995
And you can see this at work in Ratchet & Clank,

224
00:13:05,755 --> 00:13:07,016
on which Cerny consulted.

225
00:13:08,583 --> 00:13:10,965
whereby if you complete the first planet,

226
00:13:11,425 --> 00:13:13,106
three or four planets become opened up to you.

227
00:13:14,707 --> 00:13:16,429
And you can complete them in any way that you like.

228
00:13:17,209 --> 00:13:18,430
Once you've completed one of the planets,

229
00:13:18,590 --> 00:13:21,292
you get a new cool gadget or a weapon

230
00:13:22,353 --> 00:13:25,094
that lets you open up new and alternate paths

231
00:13:25,575 --> 00:13:27,576
on the other planets.

232
00:13:28,016 --> 00:13:29,357
And it's this constant flow of gadgets

233
00:13:29,777 --> 00:13:33,100
that keeps the player engaged as he learns to use them.

234
00:13:34,561 --> 00:13:36,642
Which is why good level design

235
00:13:38,084 --> 00:13:39,844
constantly teaches the player something new.

