In this book, Rafe Koster says that the human mind

244
00:14:03,669 --> 00:14:05,270
enjoys processing patterns.

245
00:14:06,282 --> 00:14:07,785
for storage and retrieval later.

246
00:14:08,366 --> 00:14:11,531
A lot of the fun in playing games is derived from this pattern analysis.

247
00:14:12,693 --> 00:14:14,857
If this pattern analysis ends too soon,

248
00:14:14,877 --> 00:14:18,162
this processing stops and the enjoyment ends.

249
00:14:19,887 --> 00:14:22,449
So how do we prolong this enjoyment through good level design?

250
00:14:23,229 --> 00:14:28,113
Well, each level in your game should introduce, showcase, or subvert a key mechanic.

251
00:14:28,774 --> 00:14:32,757
Now again, holistic design of all of the levels in your game is important for this to work

252
00:14:32,817 --> 00:14:35,159
because you have to pace it out throughout the entire game.

253
00:14:36,119 --> 00:14:40,883
The best example of this constant teaching is any game in the Zelda series.

254
00:14:42,524 --> 00:14:46,247
So when you get into a new dungeon in any Zelda game...

255
00:14:47,038 --> 00:14:48,299
you pick up a new piece of equipment.

256
00:14:48,899 --> 00:14:50,660
And each room in the dungeon

257
00:14:51,200 --> 00:14:53,901
teaches you a different way to use that piece of equipment.

258
00:14:55,281 --> 00:14:56,782
Then the final boss in that dungeon

259
00:14:57,462 --> 00:14:59,122
tests your mastery of the piece of equipment

260
00:14:59,382 --> 00:15:00,983
before it even lets you out of the dungeon.

261
00:15:02,643 --> 00:15:04,884
On top of that, when you get out into the open world,

262
00:15:05,464 --> 00:15:08,165
you're constantly asked to learn new ways

263
00:15:08,205 --> 00:15:10,346
of using your equipment to access hidden areas

264
00:15:10,466 --> 00:15:11,966
and find all of those heart containers

265
00:15:12,007 --> 00:15:13,987
and large rupee chests and so on and so forth.

266
00:15:15,649 --> 00:15:16,570
But it doesn't stop there.

267
00:15:16,730 --> 00:15:20,953
Even the game's final boss usually requires the player

268
00:15:21,654 --> 00:15:25,357
to use every single bit of equipment in an unusual way.

269
00:15:27,459 --> 00:15:29,180
And this is quite similar to the loop

270
00:15:29,200 --> 00:15:33,504
that Bethesda used to paste their games, which is learn,

271
00:15:34,104 --> 00:15:36,586
play, challenge, surprise.

272
00:15:37,667 --> 00:15:42,151
They'll teach the mechanics of the player explicitly.

273
00:15:43,310 --> 00:15:45,271
Then they'll provide a safe area with no threats,

274
00:15:45,611 --> 00:15:48,833
and all the toys that the player needs to kind of muck around

275
00:15:48,873 --> 00:15:49,673
and play with the mechanic.

276
00:15:50,974 --> 00:15:53,835
Then they'll bring in some threat or a compelling objective

277
00:15:53,875 --> 00:15:56,897
to challenge the player's mastery of that mechanic.

278
00:15:57,797 --> 00:15:59,438
And then just when the player is feeling comfortable,

279
00:16:00,959 --> 00:16:02,379
they'll do something crazy to surprise him.

280
00:16:05,160 --> 00:16:07,562
And this is why the next principle

281
00:16:08,862 --> 00:16:11,543
is that good level design is surprising.

282
00:16:18,076 --> 00:16:21,777
Now this may seem pretty obvious, but a lot of designers forget about this.

283
00:16:21,997 --> 00:16:26,159
And by surprising I don't mean that you should just fill your level with loads of monsters

284
00:16:26,179 --> 00:16:27,039
jumping out of closets.

285
00:16:28,099 --> 00:16:31,440
What I'm trying to say is that you need to keep everything fresh by not falling into

286
00:16:31,481 --> 00:16:31,981
a routine.

287
00:16:32,001 --> 00:16:38,383
Now I'm sure all of you are super familiar with the classic rollercoaster pacing method

288
00:16:38,403 --> 00:16:41,164
which is used to pace pretty much everything in video games.

289
00:16:41,644 --> 00:16:46,145
So you have steadily increasing crescendos of intensity.

290
00:16:48,651 --> 00:16:51,832
punctuated by troughs of slightly lower intensity

291
00:16:52,072 --> 00:16:53,753
so as not to desensitize the player.

292
00:16:54,733 --> 00:16:57,854
And this pattern is repeated throughout all the levels

293
00:16:57,894 --> 00:16:59,495
and throughout all the mechanics in most games

294
00:17:00,495 --> 00:17:01,735
almost to a fractal level.

295
00:17:03,136 --> 00:17:05,637
And it's my belief that if you do this in a game

296
00:17:06,637 --> 00:17:08,878
it becomes predictable pretty fast.

297
00:17:11,666 --> 00:17:15,249
So Alex Mandryka, who was formerly the creative director at Relic,

298
00:17:15,929 --> 00:17:17,210
wrote a paper on Game of Sutra,

299
00:17:18,131 --> 00:17:22,034
in which he explained that fun is actually created through uncertainty.

300
00:17:22,815 --> 00:17:25,717
And by constantly flipping the player in and out of his comfort zone,

301
00:17:26,478 --> 00:17:27,739
you can create quite a lot of fun.

302
00:17:29,180 --> 00:17:31,682
And the best way to do this is to be subversive,

303
00:17:31,782 --> 00:17:33,724
to take an existing game design paradigm,

304
00:17:34,164 --> 00:17:36,406
like the aforementioned pacing, and flip it.

305
00:17:38,235 --> 00:17:42,557
My favorite example of this is the Ishimura level in Dead Space 2.

306
00:17:42,958 --> 00:17:44,318
Has everyone here played Dead Space 2?

307
00:17:46,459 --> 00:17:48,460
Well, not as many people as I thought.

308
00:17:48,961 --> 00:17:50,461
That's upsetting, because Dead Space 2 is ace.

309
00:17:52,662 --> 00:17:54,283
Is anyone here going to play Dead Space 2?

310
00:17:54,323 --> 00:17:56,204
Because I'm about to spoil the Ishimura level.

311
00:17:57,945 --> 00:17:58,645
Well, that's a shame.

312
00:17:58,966 --> 00:18:01,427
Anyway, so when you get to the Ishimura in Dead Space 2,

313
00:18:01,487 --> 00:18:03,028
the Ishimura is the spaceship from Dead Space 1.

314
00:18:04,353 --> 00:18:06,334
You've been fighting Necromorphs all the way through the game.

315
00:18:07,374 --> 00:18:08,274
And you get to the issue and you think,

316
00:18:08,294 --> 00:18:11,495
this is the spaceship from Dead Space 1, this is going to be full of nasty aliens.

317
00:18:11,955 --> 00:18:12,395
And you get in,

318
00:18:13,455 --> 00:18:13,735
nothing.

319
00:18:14,735 --> 00:18:16,136
You're like, oh, okay, that's a bit strange.

320
00:18:16,956 --> 00:18:18,136
Five minutes later, it's the level,

321
00:18:18,156 --> 00:18:19,256
you're thinking, okay, right,

322
00:18:20,056 --> 00:18:21,637
bring on the aliens, nothing.

323
00:18:23,017 --> 00:18:25,357
Ten minutes into the level, you're like,

324
00:18:26,557 --> 00:18:27,518
shit, where are the aliens?

325
00:18:28,198 --> 00:18:29,238
There's still no aliens.

326
00:18:29,518 --> 00:18:31,678
And it's not until fifteen minutes into the Ishimura level...

327
00:18:32,620 --> 00:18:35,163
when you reach the spaceship's central transport corridor,

328
00:18:36,083 --> 00:18:38,265
this massive, great big monster drops from the ceiling,

329
00:18:38,325 --> 00:18:39,827
and at this point, you're ready to wet yourself,

330
00:18:40,027 --> 00:18:41,148
figuratively speaking, obviously.

331
00:18:43,570 --> 00:18:45,552
And this is quite cool, so they've disrupted this pacing.

332
00:18:46,333 --> 00:18:48,194
I'm quite lucky to know the producer on that level,

333
00:18:48,975 --> 00:18:50,857
and when I found out that he was responsible,

334
00:18:50,877 --> 00:18:51,497
I was really excited.

335
00:18:51,517 --> 00:18:54,059
I was like, Matt, Matt, how did you work out

336
00:18:54,099 --> 00:18:55,300
this paradigm shift?

337
00:18:55,341 --> 00:18:56,181
It's brilliant.

338
00:18:56,201 --> 00:18:57,643
Did you watch a lot of horror movies?

339
00:18:58,503 --> 00:18:58,804
Did you...

340
00:19:00,177 --> 00:19:01,977
read, take a course on horror writing,

341
00:19:02,538 --> 00:19:04,738
did you do loads of tests and do psychometric analysis,

342
00:19:04,778 --> 00:19:05,319
how did you do it?

343
00:19:05,339 --> 00:19:07,199
He goes, well no, we didn't really have any choice

344
00:19:07,640 --> 00:19:08,660
because we didn't have time to build

345
00:19:08,720 --> 00:19:11,621
any new level geometry, so we had to reuse

346
00:19:11,661 --> 00:19:14,262
the old Ishimura, and we weren't allowed to change it

347
00:19:14,282 --> 00:19:15,503
because that would mess with the canon,

348
00:19:16,863 --> 00:19:19,504
and the game director was very insistent

349
00:19:19,564 --> 00:19:21,285
that we showcase this massive big monster

350
00:19:21,325 --> 00:19:22,985
and he wouldn't let us use any other monsters

351
00:19:23,046 --> 00:19:24,446
as the first encounter in the level,

352
00:19:24,686 --> 00:19:25,907
so we didn't have a choice.

353
00:19:28,250 --> 00:19:30,091
And this kind of worked out quite well,

354
00:19:30,471 --> 00:19:31,852
because this restrictive design

355
00:19:32,473 --> 00:19:35,975
has really forced my friend to take a big risk with the pacing.

356
00:19:43,201 --> 00:19:45,122
And taking risks is important if you want to stand out.

357
00:19:49,205 --> 00:19:52,027
Now, it's easy for me to stand up here and talk about taking risks.

358
00:19:53,568 --> 00:19:54,409
I see now it's working.

359
00:19:55,084 --> 00:19:59,367
It's important for me, it's easy for me to stand up here and talk about taking risks, but...

360
00:20:01,508 --> 00:20:05,411
We all know that the problem with risks is that they are inherently risky.

361
00:20:06,892 --> 00:20:09,674
It's the designer's responsibility to manage this risk sensibly.

362
00:20:10,054 --> 00:20:13,857
So design your levels diligently on paper, but don't forget that what looks good on paper

363
00:20:14,417 --> 00:20:16,138
doesn't always work once you get it into the game.

364
00:20:16,699 --> 00:20:18,220
And oddly enough, the reverse of this is true.

365
00:20:18,260 --> 00:20:21,482
Sometimes some really ridiculous ideas actually work very well when you test them in game.

366
00:20:22,222 --> 00:20:28,087
It's absolutely crucial that if you've got anything risky, you greybox it and test it as soon as possible.

367
00:20:28,668 --> 00:20:32,992
Otherwise, you'll risk getting it cut as your game hurdles toward its next milestone

368
00:20:33,032 --> 00:20:35,434
and your producer's looking at this crazy idea and thinking,

369
00:20:35,954 --> 00:20:37,636
mmm, that's a bit risky, I'm going to cut it.

370
00:20:40,598 --> 00:20:44,682
So on Medal of Honor, we designed these awesome little, kind of, grenade puzzles.

371
00:20:45,427 --> 00:20:47,128
where you could access hidden areas of the level

372
00:20:47,468 --> 00:20:48,869
by chucking grenades down vents

373
00:20:49,029 --> 00:20:51,731
and flushing Nazis out of otherwise impregnable bunkers.

374
00:20:52,332 --> 00:20:54,253
Unfortunately, very late in production,

375
00:20:54,273 --> 00:20:55,114
we hadn't proved it out.

376
00:20:55,314 --> 00:20:55,994
It wasn't quite working.

377
00:20:56,034 --> 00:20:56,955
It ended up getting cut

378
00:20:58,156 --> 00:20:59,417
just because we hadn't tested it enough

379
00:20:59,657 --> 00:21:00,718
or we hadn't tested it early enough.

380
00:21:01,499 --> 00:21:02,339
And this was a big shame

381
00:21:02,379 --> 00:21:03,980
because it would have really helped

382
00:21:04,040 --> 00:21:05,822
towards a feeling of player empowerment.

383
00:21:07,623 --> 00:21:08,083
And the next...

384
00:21:08,784 --> 00:21:10,485
This is my favorite slide.

385
00:21:11,266 --> 00:21:12,767
The next principle is that good level design...

386
00:21:14,090 --> 00:21:15,811
empowers the player.

387
00:21:19,933 --> 00:21:22,995
The 18th century poet, Johann Wolfgang von Goethe,

388
00:21:23,015 --> 00:21:24,796
and for those of you that were born after 1985,

389
00:21:25,316 --> 00:21:26,577
that's him in the picture.

390
00:21:31,299 --> 00:21:33,781
Goethe said that you should dream no small dreams,

391
00:21:34,621 --> 00:21:37,082
for they have no power to move the hearts of men.

392
00:21:38,183 --> 00:21:39,964
And I think this is the 18th century equivalent

393
00:21:40,484 --> 00:21:42,205
of the phrase, go big or go home.

394
00:21:43,699 --> 00:21:45,341
And as a level designer, you should definitely do this.

395
00:21:45,381 --> 00:21:46,642
You should eschew the mundane.

396
00:21:46,862 --> 00:21:48,984
You should never give your player shopping list missions.

397
00:21:49,124 --> 00:21:51,566
Because essentially, video games are escapism.

398
00:21:51,966 --> 00:21:54,328
And why would people want to escape to somewhere that they

399
00:21:54,348 --> 00:21:55,389
could go in real life?

400
00:21:55,910 --> 00:21:58,612
Because quite frankly, real life sucks.

401
00:21:59,993 --> 00:22:03,716
Has anyone here seen the TV show Charlie

402
00:22:03,736 --> 00:22:04,617
Brooker's Games Wipe?

403
00:22:06,885 --> 00:22:09,448
Wow, almost as many people who've played Dead Space 2.

404
00:22:10,729 --> 00:22:14,272
You should see this, it's actually the most entertaining piece of TV

405
00:22:14,413 --> 00:22:16,254
ever made about video games, in my opinion anyway.

406
00:22:16,895 --> 00:22:17,636
And it's on YouTube.

407
00:22:18,737 --> 00:22:19,918
But anyway, in this TV show,

408
00:22:20,518 --> 00:22:24,622
the Irish comedian Dara O'Brien explains why he's never got to the third island

409
00:22:24,662 --> 00:22:25,203
in GTA 4.

410
00:22:26,697 --> 00:22:31,879
because there's this mission where he has to drive all the way across town in rush hour traffic

411
00:22:32,679 --> 00:22:34,780
and he has to drive carefully so as not to upset the police

412
00:22:35,240 --> 00:22:36,601
and he has to go through a toll bridge

413
00:22:36,621 --> 00:22:40,703
he even has to pay the toll, he has to drive carefully through the gates and not crash

414
00:22:40,743 --> 00:22:42,423
he can't speed through otherwise he'll upset the police

415
00:22:42,703 --> 00:22:46,665
and if he gets caught by the police he gets arrested and he has to go right back to the start and do it again

416
00:22:46,945 --> 00:22:48,566
and he was playing this one afternoon and he thought

417
00:22:49,998 --> 00:22:52,860
Hang on a second, I can drive in rush hour traffic in real life.

418
00:22:52,960 --> 00:22:54,461
What am I doing playing this video game?

419
00:22:54,481 --> 00:22:56,982
So he just stopped, and he's never got to the last island on GTA.

420
00:22:58,583 --> 00:23:02,065
In most games, players want to be badasses.

421
00:23:02,766 --> 00:23:06,468
And a title that does this really well is Red Faction Guerrilla.

422
00:23:06,969 --> 00:23:10,291
And it really delivers the fantasy of being a Martian rebel.

423
00:23:10,671 --> 00:23:13,173
It doesn't give you a mission to drive across a toll bridge.

424
00:23:13,893 --> 00:23:16,595
It gives you a mission to destroy a toll bridge

425
00:23:17,075 --> 00:23:19,356
using a sniper rifle that vaporizes metal.

426
00:23:21,315 --> 00:23:22,755
Now this is super, super empowering,

427
00:23:24,296 --> 00:23:30,098
as it lets the player see his effect on the environment straight away.

428
00:23:30,559 --> 00:23:32,800
And the key gameplay mechanic in Red Faction really helps this,

429
00:23:32,820 --> 00:23:33,980
the destructible terrain.

430
00:23:34,060 --> 00:23:36,301
So this is kind of an unfair example.

431
00:23:36,681 --> 00:23:38,242
But whilst this mechanic does help,

432
00:23:38,702 --> 00:23:41,383
you don't need such an obvious mechanic to do this in your levels

433
00:23:42,604 --> 00:23:46,125
if you design them to show the player's influence.

434
00:23:48,886 --> 00:23:50,247
I like the way that Infamous does this.

435
00:23:51,132 --> 00:23:56,654
So many missions in Infamous necessitate a karmic choice of some sort.

436
00:23:56,834 --> 00:23:59,235
You can either be good or you can be evil when you complete the mission.

437
00:23:59,855 --> 00:24:03,656
And in fact, this karma system is peripherated

438
00:24:04,177 --> 00:24:05,977
throughout the entire open-world environment.

439
00:24:06,378 --> 00:24:08,158
For example, there are bombs throughout the town,

440
00:24:08,578 --> 00:24:10,459
which you can either defuse to save people,

441
00:24:11,039 --> 00:24:13,980
or you can let them explode and absorb their power and become stronger,

442
00:24:14,020 --> 00:24:15,741
but as a result, collateral damage.

443
00:24:16,782 --> 00:24:18,922
Now, a karma system isn't particularly special in a game.

444
00:24:18,942 --> 00:24:19,903
There are lots of games that do it.

445
00:24:22,169 --> 00:24:28,111
But what Infamous does really well is the subtle ways in which it shows the consequence of your karmic choices.

446
00:24:29,092 --> 00:24:33,373
So, for example, the citizens of the city, citizens of the city,

447
00:24:36,043 --> 00:24:39,324
If you take good karmic choices, the better you become, the more they'll help you.

448
00:24:39,864 --> 00:24:42,085
So, they'll start cheering when you walk past,

449
00:24:42,185 --> 00:24:44,366
or they'll start throwing rocks at the bad guys you're trying to fight.

450
00:24:44,446 --> 00:24:47,186
And conversely, if you're evil, they'll start booing you,

451
00:24:47,646 --> 00:24:48,787
in a kind of pantomime style,

452
00:24:49,407 --> 00:24:50,707
and then they'll start throwing rocks at you,

453
00:24:51,067 --> 00:24:54,048
which is a kind of nice little way of showing the player that his actions

454
00:24:54,688 --> 00:24:55,648
do have a consequence.

455
00:24:57,441 --> 00:25:02,905
In Medal of Honor, we put allied hostages in some of the levels that you could rescue.

456
00:25:03,366 --> 00:25:06,568
And if you rescue these hostages, they'd pop up later on in the level to help you out.

457
00:25:07,188 --> 00:25:10,531
So depending on how you played some of the levels, if you were a little more daring,

458
00:25:10,951 --> 00:25:12,252
they'd be a little easier later on.

459
00:25:14,074 --> 00:25:16,015
Which leads me to the next principle,

460
00:25:16,956 --> 00:25:21,620
that good level design is easy, medium, and hard.

461
00:25:23,361 --> 00:25:24,422
Now what on earth does this mean?

462
00:25:24,462 --> 00:25:25,823
How can a level be easy, medium, and hard?

463
00:25:26,294 --> 00:25:30,297
Well, I've got to confess that I've got a bit of a

464
00:25:30,337 --> 00:25:32,198
bee in my bonnet or an axe to grind or what have you

465
00:25:32,719 --> 00:25:35,241
with the standard difficulty select screen

466
00:25:35,261 --> 00:25:36,562
that you see in a lot of video games.

467
00:25:38,143 --> 00:25:41,706
I think it's archaic. It asks the player to make an arbitrary choice

468
00:25:42,406 --> 00:25:44,788
which will affect how the entire game

469
00:25:45,088 --> 00:25:47,450
handles for him or her with no knowledge

470
00:25:47,490 --> 00:25:49,651
of how his skill stacks up against the game mechanics.

471
00:25:51,333 --> 00:25:52,714
Why can't the player choose in-game

472
00:25:53,794 --> 00:25:54,835
simply by playing the game?

473
00:25:56,112 --> 00:25:59,074
I'm of course alluding to the use of risk reward.

474
00:26:00,114 --> 00:26:02,115
So this works in terms of level design

475
00:26:02,596 --> 00:26:04,697
by designing multiple pathways through your level.

476
00:26:05,057 --> 00:26:06,978
So you always design the basic path through your level

477
00:26:07,578 --> 00:26:09,319
to present an easy to medium challenge.

478
00:26:10,700 --> 00:26:13,681
And then you have clearly called out high risk paths

479
00:26:14,282 --> 00:26:16,162
with an obvious reward or conversely,

480
00:26:16,863 --> 00:26:20,465
easier paths if your main path starts to get a little tough.

481
00:26:21,445 --> 00:26:22,326
And it's important when you do this

482
00:26:22,346 --> 00:26:23,706
to use the visual language that I mentioned

483
00:26:23,726 --> 00:26:24,727
in the first principle.

484
00:26:25,745 --> 00:26:27,426
And the king of risk-reward in games is...

485
00:26:28,907 --> 00:26:29,367
Burnout.

486
00:26:31,128 --> 00:26:33,109
Now in Burnout, on the tracks,

487
00:26:33,269 --> 00:26:34,430
there's always, there are always

488
00:26:34,970 --> 00:26:36,811
narrow shortcuts. They're clearly more risky

489
00:26:36,851 --> 00:26:37,652
because they're narrow.

490
00:26:38,352 --> 00:26:41,014
They're always called out by a bright yellow barricade

491
00:26:41,054 --> 00:26:42,114
which is their visual language.

492
00:26:44,316 --> 00:26:45,176
And they always provide

493
00:26:45,196 --> 00:26:45,876
a really obvious

494
00:26:46,997 --> 00:26:48,958
reduction in your lap time, or some sweet

495
00:26:49,058 --> 00:26:50,099
air so you can get some boost.

496
00:26:51,425 --> 00:26:53,607
There's no difficulty select screen in Burnout,

497
00:26:54,387 --> 00:26:57,089
because the players can select their own difficulty dynamically.

498
00:26:59,130 --> 00:27:00,772
And this isn't just applicable to racing games.

499
00:27:03,934 --> 00:27:05,395
You can use a multi-layered approach

500
00:27:06,415 --> 00:27:08,156
in RPGs, action adventures,

501
00:27:08,657 --> 00:27:09,597
first-person shooters.

502
00:27:11,299 --> 00:27:12,419
You can place a powerful weapon

503
00:27:12,800 --> 00:27:13,820
in a tricky-to-reach spot,

504
00:27:14,901 --> 00:27:16,342
necessitating navigational risk.

505
00:27:17,227 --> 00:27:20,769
you can place a dangerous enemy with a clearly called out flanking route

506
00:27:21,209 --> 00:27:24,370
allowing people who are skilled in stealth an opportunity to reduce the risk.

507
00:27:25,670 --> 00:27:29,652
These side paths can also be a puzzle requiring a little more cerebral skill

508
00:27:30,052 --> 00:27:33,453
to access. For an example, an object that can be seen

509
00:27:33,793 --> 00:27:35,694
but the root of that object is hidden

510
00:27:36,394 --> 00:27:38,515
or secret areas that are called out with a visual cue.

511
00:27:40,375 --> 00:27:44,356
I still have a slight problem with flickering neon lights.

512
00:27:45,237 --> 00:27:48,017
Every time I'm near one, I feel compelled to look for secret doors,

513
00:27:48,118 --> 00:27:50,278
because I played too much Doom when I was at university.

514
00:27:52,619 --> 00:27:55,820
So games like Dishonored use this layered approach to good effect.

515
00:27:57,960 --> 00:27:59,501
They fill the level with multiple paths,

516
00:28:00,001 --> 00:28:02,161
various styles and various aptitudes of player.

517
00:28:05,668 --> 00:28:08,072
And this, uh, these multiple gameplay layers

518
00:28:08,332 --> 00:28:10,135
also extend the replayability of their levels,

519
00:28:10,475 --> 00:28:11,917
which makes for efficient design.

520
00:28:13,480 --> 00:28:14,361
And good level design.

521
00:28:15,499 --> 00:28:21,903
is efficient. Now, this is classic data ramps. A video game always has a very finite amount

522
00:28:21,923 --> 00:28:26,606
of resources, whether that's the technical limitations of the hardware that you're developing

523
00:28:26,666 --> 00:28:32,650
on, such as the memory or the pixel pushing power, to the real world constraints like

524
00:28:32,810 --> 00:28:36,473
your production schedule, the number of people on your team, the scope of your projects,

525
00:28:36,533 --> 00:28:42,057
and so on. And it's a designer's responsibility to maximize the use of those resources.

526
00:28:43,026 --> 00:28:46,048
And for level design, this means not only using the whole animal nose to tail,

527
00:28:46,548 --> 00:28:48,550
but doing it more than once, and doing it quickly.

528
00:28:51,692 --> 00:28:53,553
For this, modular design is your friend.

529
00:28:54,774 --> 00:28:57,055
A good level designer doesn't create a level,

530
00:28:57,615 --> 00:29:00,617
he creates a series of modular, mechanic-driven encounters

531
00:29:01,358 --> 00:29:02,999
that you can string together to make a level.

532
00:29:04,260 --> 00:29:04,880
And another level.

533
00:29:05,641 --> 00:29:06,241
And another level.

534
00:29:08,352 --> 00:29:14,456
On top of this, this technique also creates a series of familiar moments that the player can use to learn and master your mechanics.

535
00:29:15,096 --> 00:29:19,518
I don't know if any of you have had a chance to check out the toolkits that ship with Bethesda games,

536
00:29:20,239 --> 00:29:21,960
but these are extremely modular.

537
00:29:22,340 --> 00:29:27,743
They're essentially like medieval Lego or post-apocalyptic Lego, depending on which game you're playing with.

538
00:29:28,843 --> 00:29:34,467
And it's through this modularity that such a relatively small team can create such a massive amount of content.

539
00:29:36,044 --> 00:29:39,545
And also by applying simple modifiers to these modules,

540
00:29:39,785 --> 00:29:41,285
it's possible to create variation

541
00:29:41,625 --> 00:29:44,266
and keep things fresh by providing increased challenge

542
00:29:44,626 --> 00:29:45,266
and surprise.

543
00:29:46,386 --> 00:29:49,047
Modifiers are particularly important for creating

544
00:29:50,407 --> 00:29:51,647
bi-directional gameplay.

545
00:29:53,508 --> 00:29:56,388
Now, your level artists or your world artists

546
00:29:56,828 --> 00:29:59,069
are going to spend a lot of time making the levels that you

547
00:29:59,089 --> 00:29:59,349
design.

548
00:30:00,614 --> 00:30:01,195
look beautiful.

549
00:30:01,915 --> 00:30:05,879
When the unfortunate reality is that most players will blitz through them in a matter

550
00:30:05,899 --> 00:30:06,360
of seconds.

551
00:30:07,081 --> 00:30:11,785
Now, how do you keep your level artists happy and get the most bang for your art buck?

552
00:30:12,886 --> 00:30:15,389
Well, you need to reuse the nice artwork from your level.

553
00:30:16,290 --> 00:30:19,373
Now the most obvious way to do this is to make your player backtrack a lot.

554
00:30:19,733 --> 00:30:21,215
But backtracking is totally not cool.

555
00:30:22,719 --> 00:30:25,320
What you should do instead is design for bi-directional gameplay.

556
00:30:25,781 --> 00:30:28,602
So what I mean by that is, gameplay on the way there

557
00:30:29,322 --> 00:30:31,583
is totally different to gameplay on the way back.

558
00:30:32,063 --> 00:30:34,665
And a game series that does this very well is Halo.

559
00:30:35,465 --> 00:30:39,087
So for example, in Halo 1, the level 343 Guilty Spark

560
00:30:39,107 --> 00:30:40,507
is awesome for bi-directionality.

561
00:30:40,527 --> 00:30:43,689
It begins as a search mission with exploratory gameplay

562
00:30:44,389 --> 00:30:47,251
and then when you unleash the flood, all hell breaks loose

563
00:30:47,351 --> 00:30:49,051
and it's intense combat on the way back.

564
00:30:50,267 --> 00:30:53,069
Similarly, in Halo 3, in the mission, The Ark,

565
00:30:53,990 --> 00:30:56,832
you fight through a desert level on foot using a sniper rifle.

566
00:30:56,932 --> 00:30:58,413
And then when you get to the mission to Apex,

567
00:30:58,894 --> 00:31:00,115
you get a tank air dropped in.

568
00:31:00,175 --> 00:31:01,996
And you can blast your way out of the level in a tank.

569
00:31:02,897 --> 00:31:04,198
Totally, totally different gameplay.

570
00:31:08,382 --> 00:31:09,703
Expanding on this principle further,

571
00:31:10,143 --> 00:31:11,745
levels, and in fact, the entire game,

572
00:31:12,385 --> 00:31:14,467
can be made totally nonlinear.

573
00:31:15,748 --> 00:31:20,889
A great way of doing this is to provide implicit objectives that require intuition and exploration

574
00:31:20,929 --> 00:31:21,470
to complete.

575
00:31:22,050 --> 00:31:26,831
So the skulls in Halo, the cog tags in Gears of War, and the feathers in Assassin's Creed.

576
00:31:28,772 --> 00:31:33,093
These are all designed to encourage non-linear exploration and extend the gameplay with no

577
00:31:33,153 --> 00:31:34,073
extra hit production.

578
00:31:34,474 --> 00:31:37,835
But these are actually not great examples of non-linear gameplay.

579
00:31:39,474 --> 00:31:43,737
Because it's very important that you don't create gameplay for gameplay's sake.

580
00:31:43,757 --> 00:31:44,818
Just to pad out your game.

581
00:31:44,838 --> 00:31:49,861
You need to keep your non-linearity relevant by incentivizing the player by calling out

582
00:31:50,201 --> 00:31:51,542
clearly the reward in advance.

583
00:31:52,003 --> 00:31:54,805
The heart in Dishonored is a great example of this.

584
00:31:55,345 --> 00:32:00,529
In fact, you should also try and tie these objectives into the main narrative thread.

585
00:32:01,549 --> 00:32:08,414
There's this awesome old Game Boy Advance game called Astro Boy Omega Factor.

586
00:32:09,370 --> 00:32:10,371
that does this beautifully,

587
00:32:11,652 --> 00:32:14,193
by actually making replaying the levels a key narrative element.

588
00:32:14,433 --> 00:32:16,294
Once you've finished the game and played through all the levels,

589
00:32:16,694 --> 00:32:19,056
you're treated to a really quite a disappointing ending.

590
00:32:19,836 --> 00:32:21,497
But somebody appears and sends Astro Boy

591
00:32:21,977 --> 00:32:23,838
all the way back in time to the start of the game

592
00:32:24,359 --> 00:32:27,200
with all of the power-ups and weapons that he's collected.

593
00:32:27,700 --> 00:32:29,782
He can then play through the game,

594
00:32:30,322 --> 00:32:31,883
zapping backwards and forwards in time,

595
00:32:31,983 --> 00:32:34,204
using all of his different power-ups to select the levels,

596
00:32:34,564 --> 00:32:36,465
defeat monsters that he couldn't defeat before,

597
00:32:36,886 --> 00:32:37,926
open up secret areas.

598
00:32:39,171 --> 00:32:43,054
and ultimately get the much more rewarding, true conclusion to the game.

599
00:32:43,555 --> 00:32:48,579
So essentially, what this plot device does is massage the player into playing through the entire game.

600
00:32:49,380 --> 00:32:49,760
Twice.

601
00:32:50,661 --> 00:32:52,382
Which is pretty cool, because when you do complete it,

602
00:32:53,183 --> 00:32:54,864
the finale is really emotional.

603
00:33:00,649 --> 00:33:04,672
Which is why rule number nine is that good level design creates emotion.

604
00:33:06,192 --> 00:33:10,474
Last year, the US Supreme Court, there they are, bless their little cotton socks,

605
00:33:11,794 --> 00:33:16,897
declared that video games were legally art, which is ace.

606
00:33:18,378 --> 00:33:20,559
According to the dictionary, art is

607
00:33:21,079 --> 00:33:25,942
the quality, production, expression, or realm, according to aesthetic principles,

608
00:33:26,402 --> 00:33:30,684
of what is beautiful, appealing, or of more than ordinary significance.

609
00:33:31,920 --> 00:33:34,621
This is a kind of dry, pragmatic definition of art for me.

610
00:33:35,521 --> 00:33:39,003
From a purely subjective and personal standpoint,

611
00:33:39,563 --> 00:33:41,764
I like to think of art as anything that's been specifically created

612
00:33:41,804 --> 00:33:43,685
to provoke an emotional reaction.

613
00:33:44,665 --> 00:33:48,707
So paintings, sculpture, photography, music, movies,

614
00:33:49,527 --> 00:33:52,088
all of these are created to encourage some kind of emotional response

615
00:33:52,628 --> 00:33:53,329
in their recipient.

616
00:33:53,769 --> 00:33:56,430
This is particularly true for an interactive medium like video games.

617
00:33:57,410 --> 00:34:00,532
Now the most analogous form of art to level design

618
00:34:01,258 --> 00:34:03,176
is, surprise, surprise, architecture.

619
00:34:04,245 --> 00:34:06,026
And architects have been playing with people's emotions

620
00:34:06,426 --> 00:34:07,706
for hundreds and hundreds of years.

621
00:34:07,766 --> 00:34:09,547
And there are loads of great architectural theories

622
00:34:09,827 --> 00:34:10,848
that we can steal from them.

623
00:34:11,788 --> 00:34:12,769
For example, windows.

624
00:34:13,469 --> 00:34:15,550
If windows are placed below knee height,

625
00:34:16,431 --> 00:34:18,152
that's because the architect wanted to convey

626
00:34:18,312 --> 00:34:20,333
the feeling of power and voyeurism.

627
00:34:22,294 --> 00:34:24,715
Conversely, if windows are placed above shoulder height,

628
00:34:25,195 --> 00:34:26,816
the architect wanted to invoke

629
00:34:26,916 --> 00:34:28,717
a feeling of persecution and imprisonment.

630
00:34:28,737 --> 00:34:29,957
Although I'm not entirely sure

631
00:34:29,997 --> 00:34:31,458
why an architect would want to do that

632
00:34:32,038 --> 00:34:33,299
unless he was designing a prison.

633
00:34:34,837 --> 00:34:39,484
Architects make curved rooms with no corners to induce a feeling of womb-like calm in their buildings.

634
00:34:40,666 --> 00:34:43,932
There are also a lot of classic level design tricks that you can use to create...

635
00:34:45,734 --> 00:34:46,536
spatial empathy.

636
00:34:48,681 --> 00:34:51,064
You can use tight corners to limit the player's field of view,

637
00:34:51,324 --> 00:34:53,366
to keep him tense and suspicious and claustrophobic.

638
00:34:53,947 --> 00:34:57,851
You can make your level twisty and labyrinthine to create confusion and panic.

639
00:34:58,571 --> 00:35:00,553
Alternatively, you can blow that space wide open

640
00:35:00,974 --> 00:35:04,297
to create a feeling of isolation and epic scale.

641
00:35:04,818 --> 00:35:08,842
Even switching from a narrow space to a large space is a great technique

642
00:35:09,142 --> 00:35:12,365
to force the player to look at a specific vista to create a sense of wonder.

643
00:35:13,797 --> 00:35:15,818
You can bring verticality into the mix

644
00:35:15,858 --> 00:35:17,258
to create a feeling of persecution

645
00:35:17,298 --> 00:35:18,638
by attacking the player from above,

646
00:35:19,378 --> 00:35:21,719
a feeling of vertigo by making the player scale

647
00:35:21,779 --> 00:35:23,199
a high mountain or a high building,

648
00:35:23,999 --> 00:35:25,560
or a feeling of hope by placing a reward

649
00:35:25,600 --> 00:35:26,660
at the top of a tall building.

650
00:35:28,260 --> 00:35:31,381
The new Tomb Raider does this really well.

651
00:35:32,081 --> 00:35:34,322
It goes from super narrow caves to wide open jungle

652
00:35:34,382 --> 00:35:35,982
and really leverages the space

653
00:35:36,542 --> 00:35:38,163
or lack thereof to create emotion.

654
00:35:39,303 --> 00:35:40,843
And aside from spatial empathy,

655
00:35:41,223 --> 00:35:42,143
when designing for emotion,

656
00:35:43,571 --> 00:35:46,312
I personally find that the best technique is to work backwards.

657
00:35:47,552 --> 00:35:51,554
So your starting point should be the desired emotional response you want to evoke from

658
00:35:51,574 --> 00:35:52,034
the player.

659
00:35:52,714 --> 00:35:56,636
Then you should drill down and select the spatial parameters, the narrative elements

660
00:35:56,756 --> 00:36:01,178
and mechanics that you want to use to elicit that emotion.

661
00:36:01,918 --> 00:36:07,480
So if you want to make the player feel persecuted, put an enemy AI into your level that constantly

662
00:36:07,540 --> 00:36:07,880
hunts him.

663
00:36:09,105 --> 00:36:14,210
If you want the player to feel exhilarated, engage them in a high-speed chase or a firefight

664
00:36:14,631 --> 00:36:16,412
in a large open space or an open road.

665
00:36:17,233 --> 00:36:20,777
If you want the player to feel a sense of urgency, modify your core mechanics with some

666
00:36:20,817 --> 00:36:21,578
kind of time limit.

667
00:36:22,899 --> 00:36:26,603
If you want the player to feel a sense of desperation, give them an almost impossible

668
00:36:26,643 --> 00:36:32,449
goal and then save them at the last minute, like Company of Heroes does in the Carentan

669
00:36:32,489 --> 00:36:32,709
mission.

670
00:36:33,987 --> 00:36:37,972
Now this is an interesting mission for me because in this level of Company of Heroes,

671
00:36:38,432 --> 00:36:43,678
you are asked to protect the town of Carentan against a Nazi invasion force until Allied

672
00:36:43,718 --> 00:36:44,779
reinforcements arrive.

673
00:36:45,380 --> 00:36:49,344
And so if you guys thought the same thing that I did when I was given that mission objective,

674
00:36:49,444 --> 00:36:53,068
I thought, that's cool, all I have to do is hold out for a certain amount of time.

675
00:36:54,304 --> 00:36:55,825
and then my reinforcements will arrive.

676
00:36:56,385 --> 00:36:58,845
But Company of Heroes effectively lies to the player

677
00:36:58,885 --> 00:36:59,926
about the mission parameters,

678
00:37:00,426 --> 00:37:02,546
because the reinforcements aren't triggered by a timer.

679
00:37:03,106 --> 00:37:05,907
They're triggered by the number of soldiers you have left alive.

680
00:37:06,127 --> 00:37:07,868
So they will only ever appear

681
00:37:08,288 --> 00:37:09,768
when you have two soldiers left.

682
00:37:11,689 --> 00:37:14,829
Now, this makes this battle super, super intense.

683
00:37:15,730 --> 00:37:16,230
And in fact,

684
00:37:17,650 --> 00:37:20,031
using the game mechanics like this to create emotion

685
00:37:20,391 --> 00:37:23,131
is possibly the single most important goal of a level designer.

686
00:37:23,907 --> 00:37:27,187
which is why the final principle is that good level design

687
00:37:28,067 --> 00:37:29,448
is driven by mechanics.

688
00:37:33,789 --> 00:37:36,449
Now, there's a, I read this quote somewhere on the internet,

689
00:37:36,469 --> 00:37:38,470
and apologies to whoever I'm stealing it from

690
00:37:38,510 --> 00:37:40,970
because I couldn't find it again, and I don't know who said it.

691
00:37:41,430 --> 00:37:42,130
But the quote goes,

692
00:37:43,091 --> 00:37:46,231
that books let you imagine extraordinary things.

693
00:37:47,732 --> 00:37:50,232
Movies let you see extraordinary things.

694
00:37:52,608 --> 00:37:56,750
But video games let you actually do extraordinary things.

695
00:37:58,991 --> 00:38:03,633
And so, above all else, great level design is driven by this interaction, the game's

696
00:38:03,693 --> 00:38:04,153
mechanics.

697
00:38:05,274 --> 00:38:11,297
Game levels don't just provide the context or the setting for the mechanics, they provide

698
00:38:11,317 --> 00:38:13,398
the very reality in which they exist.

699
00:38:14,518 --> 00:38:16,560
Now I'm going to apologize in advance for this next slide,

700
00:38:17,281 --> 00:38:20,084
and for the slightly highfalutin word smithery,

701
00:38:20,564 --> 00:38:22,206
but I like to describe a game's level

702
00:38:22,786 --> 00:38:24,148
as the metaphysical medium

703
00:38:24,508 --> 00:38:26,090
through which the gameplay is delivered.

704
00:38:27,231 --> 00:38:29,733
So I'm going to expand on this by means of an analogy,

705
00:38:30,234 --> 00:38:32,016
and I'd like you to think of your video game as a painting.

706
00:38:33,357 --> 00:38:35,439
So the subject of your painting, what you're painting,

707
00:38:36,060 --> 00:38:37,321
those are your gameplay mechanics,

708
00:38:37,341 --> 00:38:38,122
that's your gameplay mechanics.

709
00:38:39,295 --> 00:38:44,717
The composition, what gives your subject its context.

710
00:38:45,237 --> 00:38:47,438
That's your narrative and your graphics.

711
00:38:49,979 --> 00:38:53,020
The medium, the actual oil and canvas

712
00:38:53,060 --> 00:38:54,341
that you paint your painting with,

713
00:38:55,181 --> 00:38:56,161
is your game's level.

714
00:38:57,702 --> 00:39:00,002
Your level should be a gameplay delivery system

715
00:39:00,283 --> 00:39:02,723
whose primary function is to leverage your mechanics

716
00:39:02,783 --> 00:39:04,264
to create a great experience.

717
00:39:05,325 --> 00:39:11,271
Topology, architecture, objectives, interactions, combat scenarios, etc. should all be designed

718
00:39:12,493 --> 00:39:14,174
to showcase your game's mechanics.

719
00:39:15,876 --> 00:39:19,560
Now it's important to have a thorough understanding of your mechanics in order to do this, but

720
00:39:19,580 --> 00:39:23,023
I appreciate that this isn't always possible as your mechanics and your levels are being

721
00:39:23,063 --> 00:39:23,924
developed concurrently.

722
00:39:26,368 --> 00:39:29,309
But you should always have a rough idea of the sort of systems that are being built.

723
00:39:29,709 --> 00:39:32,110
Conversely, this can work the other way around.

724
00:39:32,790 --> 00:39:35,371
If you have, if there's something that you want that's cool in your level,

725
00:39:35,971 --> 00:39:39,572
talk to your lead mechanic engineer or your lead gameplay designer

726
00:39:39,592 --> 00:39:41,373
to see if you can get a mechanic to support it.

727
00:39:41,773 --> 00:39:44,613
In fact, interdisciplinary communication

728
00:39:45,053 --> 00:39:47,794
between engineers, designers, and artists is absolutely crucial

729
00:39:47,834 --> 00:39:49,355
if you want to have a strong level design team.

730
00:39:51,032 --> 00:39:57,154
My favorite game for, well, one of my favorite games for mechanic-based design is Deus Ex Human Revolution.

731
00:39:58,295 --> 00:40:04,477
So the levels in Deus Ex, they have multiple paths that showcase the stealth mechanics and the combat mechanics.

732
00:40:04,997 --> 00:40:08,518
They have specific moments for the player to use their augments.

733
00:40:11,219 --> 00:40:14,200
So areas where you can use your bionic arms to punch through walls,

734
00:40:14,660 --> 00:40:18,701
you'll reinforce back to lift up heavy objects and reveal new paths through the level.

735
00:40:21,775 --> 00:40:24,496
unsuspecting enemies who are standing at the bottom of a really

736
00:40:24,856 --> 00:40:28,057
