00:54:21,537 --> 00:54:24,198
You had a big arrow on the screen that told you where to go.

981
00:54:25,098 --> 00:54:26,998
The soldiers would lead you through the level.

982
00:54:27,279 --> 00:54:30,479
So they'd always leapfrog over you to guide you through the level.

983
00:54:30,499 --> 00:54:31,619
People still didn't know where to go.

984
00:54:32,860 --> 00:54:35,100
So it's quite a complex problem.

985
00:54:37,290 --> 00:54:41,852
And aside from doing the dead space or perfect dark trick

986
00:54:41,872 --> 00:54:45,754
of actually pinging on the floor and showing the player

987
00:54:45,774 --> 00:54:47,295
exactly where to go, there's no way

988
00:54:47,335 --> 00:54:50,336
that you can really explicitly direct the player somewhere

989
00:54:50,356 --> 00:54:52,257
without breaking some of the immersion, I think.

990
00:54:53,637 --> 00:54:55,018
So again, it's about finding a balance.

991
00:54:55,038 --> 00:54:56,118
That's not really a great answer,

992
00:54:56,138 --> 00:54:57,739
but hopefully that's OK.

993
00:54:58,560 --> 00:54:58,980
OK, thank you.

994
00:55:01,601 --> 00:55:03,502
Common problem that I see in game design

995
00:55:03,842 --> 00:55:05,963
is whenever you're about to battle a boss,

996
00:55:07,429 --> 00:55:09,612
I thought, he's talking without moving his lips, that's brilliant.

997
00:55:10,693 --> 00:55:14,038
Sorry, um, but whenever I'm about to fight a boss,

998
00:55:15,199 --> 00:55:17,262
you mentioned the surprise element in level design,

999
00:55:17,843 --> 00:55:20,066
but I find that I always know a boss is coming

1000
00:55:20,086 --> 00:55:21,848
because I enter a room that's just full of ammunition.

1001
00:55:22,526 --> 00:55:24,588
And I imagine that you have to combat that because like,

1002
00:55:25,588 --> 00:55:27,810
I'm the kind of guy that's gonna just burn through my grenades

1003
00:55:28,631 --> 00:55:31,713
and then I find the boss and I'm like, crap, I should have saved the grenades.

1004
00:55:31,753 --> 00:55:34,395
And so you're kind of combating against numbskulls,

1005
00:55:34,475 --> 00:55:37,758
but also destroying that surprise element.

1006
00:55:37,778 --> 00:55:38,358
Does that make sense?

1007
00:55:38,813 --> 00:55:44,775
Yeah, so that's interesting. I think what you've got there is what I like to refer to as the designer's curse.

1008
00:55:45,135 --> 00:55:49,637
So you're so familiar with the mechanics and the setup of the levels and level design

1009
00:55:50,177 --> 00:55:52,798
that you know exactly what's coming. You can preempt it.

1010
00:55:53,138 --> 00:55:54,759
I have this problem when I'm playing shooters.

1011
00:55:55,859 --> 00:55:58,680
Whenever I walk into a room that's full of boxes that come up to about here,

1012
00:55:58,700 --> 00:56:03,061
it's like, yeah, okay, there's lots of cover in this room, so people are going to pile in through the doors at the end.

1013
00:56:03,961 --> 00:56:06,742
So it puts me in a very different mindset to somebody who just be like,

1014
00:56:06,782 --> 00:56:07,743
ooh, look, crates, that's nice.

1015
00:56:09,165 --> 00:56:13,429
So yeah, I think it's difficult to design around that.

1016
00:56:13,809 --> 00:56:16,632
It almost feels like the opposite problem

1017
00:56:17,873 --> 00:56:19,214
from the previous question, where

1018
00:56:19,614 --> 00:56:22,697
you've got such a preloaded knowledge that you

1019
00:56:22,737 --> 00:56:24,338
can anticipate what's going on.

1020
00:56:24,398 --> 00:56:27,380
And that's why it's really important to disrupt

1021
00:56:27,420 --> 00:56:31,083
that kind of standard paradigm and the pacing and the layout.

1022
00:56:32,824 --> 00:56:41,928
I wouldn't be able to give you a specific example of a boss fight that comes out of nowhere apart from that day of sex example that Thomas Grip gave where you sneak around and then suddenly there's a cutscene.

1023
00:56:42,828 --> 00:56:45,289
But that's probably a bad example, so I'll stop there.

1024
00:56:46,090 --> 00:56:47,190
Does that answer your question?

1025
00:56:47,790 --> 00:56:49,371
A bit, yeah. Thank you.

1026
00:56:51,672 --> 00:56:57,994
Hi, I was recently talking to someone at a bigger studio and they were saying a lot of their setups were driven by...

1027
00:56:59,078 --> 00:57:01,639
playtesting and the feedback they were getting.

1028
00:57:01,699 --> 00:57:04,859
So testers would score it based on how fun it was.

1029
00:57:05,560 --> 00:57:07,880
And a lot of the design was being changed around

1030
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:12,021
because they were getting higher scores in certain setups.

1031
00:57:12,941 --> 00:57:14,381
So they were taking out puzzles and whatnot.

1032
00:57:15,721 --> 00:57:18,062
And so I feel like it could have potentially

1033
00:57:18,842 --> 00:57:21,362
taken away from the original creative direction.

1034
00:57:22,102 --> 00:57:23,003
What's your take on that?

1035
00:57:24,403 --> 00:57:26,243
So you're asking if.

1036
00:57:28,157 --> 00:57:30,279
consistently playtesting and updating your game

1037
00:57:30,659 --> 00:57:32,641
takes away from the initial creative vision

1038
00:57:33,162 --> 00:57:33,962
that you had in mind.

1039
00:57:34,183 --> 00:57:36,665
So this is an interesting personal point for me,

1040
00:57:36,725 --> 00:57:39,587
because whilst I think it's super, super crucial

1041
00:57:39,928 --> 00:57:41,249
to play through your levels,

1042
00:57:41,549 --> 00:57:45,172
in fact, I like in level design to...

1043
00:57:46,974 --> 00:57:48,675
Hang on. Is it level design or playing level design?

1044
00:57:51,656 --> 00:57:53,477
I like level design to having a kitchen.

1045
00:57:54,417 --> 00:57:55,438
Your level is like your kitchen.

1046
00:57:55,818 --> 00:57:59,740
When you're in your own level, you know exactly where the knives and the forks and the spatulas and the spoons are.

1047
00:58:00,380 --> 00:58:01,861
But when you cook in somebody else's kitchen,

1048
00:58:02,782 --> 00:58:04,542
it is quite stressful because you're like,

1049
00:58:04,582 --> 00:58:06,863
which drawer are the spoons in? I don't know where the pots are, what's going on?

1050
00:58:07,204 --> 00:58:11,926
And I think you've always got to bear in mind that the player is going to be cooking in your kitchen.

1051
00:58:13,352 --> 00:58:16,414
So you've got to do the best to make your kitchen

1052
00:58:16,974 --> 00:58:19,757
kind of conform to a standard layout

1053
00:58:19,797 --> 00:58:21,678
and not put your cutlery in the bottom drawer,

1054
00:58:21,698 --> 00:58:23,159
because that's weird.

1055
00:58:25,261 --> 00:58:30,385
But this always reminds me of this great Alan Moore quote,

1056
00:58:31,346 --> 00:58:33,347
who says that you shouldn't listen

1057
00:58:33,387 --> 00:58:35,729
to what anyone says about your design or your critics.

1058
00:58:37,391 --> 00:58:39,312
You need to be your critic.

1059
00:58:39,927 --> 00:58:43,347
You need some, because you know when you make something, you know how good or how bad it is.

1060
00:58:44,007 --> 00:58:51,229
So as long as you approach your initial vision with a really well-balanced type of self-criticism,

1061
00:58:51,809 --> 00:58:57,070
you should be able to accommodate the feedback you get and filter it out accordingly.

1062
00:58:58,031 --> 00:58:59,931
I think I've got time for two more questions.

1063
00:59:01,191 --> 00:59:02,132
Two minutes, two minutes left.

1064
00:59:04,314 --> 00:59:08,718
I'm curious, out of your entire career, all the levels you designed, what is the one that

1065
00:59:08,738 --> 00:59:11,159
you're the most proud of or felt was the most successful?

1066
00:59:14,502 --> 00:59:19,606
My favorite level that I've designed is the opening level to Medal of Honor Heroes 2,

1067
00:59:21,668 --> 00:59:28,393
because it's the tutorial level and it was a very early FPS on Wii, and so we had this

1068
00:59:28,473 --> 00:59:29,113
mandate to...

1069
00:59:30,443 --> 00:59:33,166
really clearly teach the player

1070
00:59:33,586 --> 00:59:37,390
the kind of crazy new motion controls of the Wii.

1071
00:59:38,892 --> 00:59:41,314
But we didn't want to make it like a boring tutorial

1072
00:59:41,514 --> 00:59:44,577
because it interrupts the flow of the level and it's very dull.

1073
00:59:47,238 --> 00:59:48,919
we actually managed to create something that

1074
00:59:49,339 --> 00:59:53,042
kind of captured the spirit of the Normandy beach landings from the original Medal of Honor.

1075
00:59:53,302 --> 00:59:55,323
But at the same time it was a tutorial.

1076
00:59:55,343 --> 00:59:59,206
So there were loads of explosions that didn't really have much of an effect on the player's health.

1077
00:59:59,566 --> 01:00:01,567
There were loads and loads of enemies,

1078
01:00:02,007 --> 01:00:05,650
but they'd shoot at your friends and not at you.

1079
01:00:06,010 --> 01:00:08,672
But if you moved past the enemies, the enemies would turn around and target you.

1080
01:00:08,692 --> 01:00:10,933
So it was a really nice tutorial.

1081
01:00:10,953 --> 01:00:12,634
It felt really exciting, it felt really intense.

1082
01:00:13,014 --> 01:00:15,996
But it also did a really good job of teaching the player the core mechanics.

1083
01:00:16,377 --> 01:00:19,959
and every section of the beach landing

1084
01:00:20,720 --> 01:00:23,282
had been designed very, very deliberately

1085
01:00:23,722 --> 01:00:25,323
to introduce a new mechanic

1086
01:00:25,383 --> 01:00:26,765
and to teach the player how to use it.

1087
01:00:26,785 --> 01:00:29,266
So it was a lot of fun for me to work on as well.

1088
01:00:29,326 --> 01:00:30,407
So I was quite pleased with that.

1089
01:00:31,608 --> 01:00:33,450
Thank you. I'm going to have to check that out.

1090
01:00:33,490 --> 01:00:34,270
Yeah, I hope you enjoy it.

1091
01:00:43,877 --> 01:00:44,218
applause

